Certainly! Here's a Java function that generates a unique string in the specified format:

```java
public class UniqueStringGenerator {
    private static int counter = 0;

    public static String generateUniqueString() {
        // Format: sharm488_000001
        String prefix = "sharm488_";
        String numericPart = String.format("%06d", counter++);
        return prefix + numericPart;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Example: calling the function multiple times
        for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
            String uniqueString = generateUniqueString();
            System.out.println(uniqueString);
        }
    }
}
```

In this code, the `generateUniqueString` function uses a static counter to keep track of the numeric part. It formats the numeric part to have leading zeros using `String.format("%06d", counter++)` to ensure it is always six digits. When you call this function multiple times, it will return unique strings with an increasing numeric part.
